Oct 20 2009 	The best birthday present ever	My partner suprised me with a 7 day trip to San Francisco. We stayed at the Executive Hotel Vintage Court and like other reviews, it doesnt look much from the outside.The interior is gorgeous and very cosy and the staff were tremendously helpful, nothing was too much trouble for them.We stayed in an executive room on the front of the hotel and the only downside to this is you do get alot of noise from the street - ie street sweepers etc - but this didnt matter to us as we were up and about early to take in as much of the city as we could.Location is perfect. Its right next door to Chinatown, literally a 2 minute walk to the nearest cable cars and less than 5 mins walk to Union Square.I dont need to go on about the sights etc in San Fran - this review is simply for the hotel - which in my view was amazing. It is only a 3* and having stayed in the 5* Sheraton in New York you'd think a 3* would be much less comparible.The rooms were cleaned every day, clean towels daily and bath robes for us to wear. The television had a mass of available channels for us to have on in the background whilst getting ready and a fully stocked mini bar incuding snacks which was great if you got the late night munchies!I whould happily recommend this hotel to anyone and if I ever go back to San Fran, I wouldnt hesitate to stay there again.	
Oct 18 2009 	Really Great Hotel 	Just got back from staying at the Executive Hotel Vintage Court. Me &amp; my partner stayed there for 10 nights and I can highly recommend it. The location is good - very close to Union Square (which is central in San Francisco). The hotel doesn't look spectacular from the outside, but inside it's great. It has a wonderful cosy lounge with really comfy settees and chairs and a gorgeous decor based on a 'winery' theme. Lovely paintings in the lounge of vintage wine and stuff. There was a log fire blazing in the lounge every day we were there, and it always felt really cozy. In the lounge area is also a computer where you can access the internet (for a fee). In the mornings in the lounge, the hotel serves delicious complimentary danish pastries, muffins and coffee and tea. In the evening between 5-6pm they service complimentary red and white wine. The hotel staff are always really helpful and friendly too. They would always immediately try to deal with any queries or anything we wanted. We stayed on the 7th floor in the room called Davis Bynum Winery. (Every room has a nameplate on the door and every room is named after a winery!) The room was very comfortable - really good comfortable bed and pillows, nice warm radiator, aircon if it got too hot, flat screen TV, ironing board, comfy chair and ensuite bathroom with a good hot shower. The maid comes every day to make up the room so it always looks clean and tidy. They also provide complementary toiletries and there is a good hairdryer in the bathroom. The only downside I suppose it that we didn't have any view from our hotel window - it just looked out on to the backs of some quite ugly backdoor buildings - not onto the street at all. But we didn't really care. I really like the location of this hotel too. It was only a 7 or 8 minute walk to Union Square, where Macy's and other shops are. About 4 minutes from the hotel is a really good book shop called Borders that is open until 11pm and has a really good coffee shop upstairs. They don't mind you borrowing books to read while you have your coffee and pumpkin bread etc. There are also Starbucks in the vicinity and a really fantastic diner called Lori's Diner that serves wonderful food at very reasonable prices. We are vegetarians and thought we would have trouble eating in the diner, but they serve lovely vegan salads and other really nice veggie food. Really good - I can highly recommend this place. Also in this same street, about a minute from the hotel is the cable car stop. This takes you right into downtown or in the other direction to Fisherman's Wharf - where all the adorable sea lions live on Pier 39. I'd advise you to get a travel pass asap though, because the transport can get pricey and you have to use it alot as the hills are enough to beat anyone. We got a 7-day pass for $24 dollars. We could use this as much as we liked. If we hadn't had this, a one-way journey on the cable car would have been $5 a time, and other public transport about $2. So it really saved us loads of money. Well I hope you like my review. I could waffle on about how great San Fran is forever, and I can highly recommend this hotel and will certainly stay there again next time I visit this city.	
